# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alcide-de-gasperi
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1911-cisleithanian-legislative-election] Legislative elections to elect members of the Imperial Council were held in Cisleithania, the Austrian section of Austria-Hungary over several days in June and July 1911.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1911-cisleithanian-legislative-election] A coalition of German national and liberal parties, the *Deutscher Nationalverband*, emerged as the largest bloc in Parliament, holding 100 of the 516 seats.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1911-cisleithanian-legislative-election] This was the second election under universal male suffrage, and the last before the dissolution of the empire as a result of World War I.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1911-cisleithanian-legislative-election] At that dissolution it was the German representatives that formed the first truly Austrian legislative body of the Republic of German-Austria.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1911-cisleithanian-legislative-election] In the German-speaking areas the results however were similar to the previous elections in 1907, with the Christian Socials as the largest party (76 seats), followed by the Social Democrats (43) and the German People's Party (32).
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1911-cisleithanian-legislative-election] Both the major parties lost seats, and the parties which gained were the moderate centre and the radicals.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1911-cisleithanian-legislative-election] Results varied by province, with Lower Austria providing the political base for the two largest parties.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1911-cisleithanian-legislative-election] There was a wide difference between rural areas (Christian Social) and urban (Social Democrat), a split (social cleavage) that had become more evident since 1907, with the Christian Socials losing their support in the outer belt of Viennese districts.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1911-cisleithanian-legislative-election] Support for the German People's Party was more even.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1911-cisleithanian-legislative-election] The German People's Party found its support in the middle strata of Austrian society.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1911-cisleithanian-legislative-election] On the other hand, industrialists rejected this party in favour of the *Freisinnige* group, particularly the German Progressive Party, as did the more prosperous merchants.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1911-cisleithanian-legislative-election] Among the non-German nationalities, the results also differed widely between nations.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1911-cisleithanian-legislative-election] Ran as the Polish Clerical Party in Silesia.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1911-cisleithanian-legislative-election] Ran as the Slovenian Clerical Party in Styria and Gorizia and Gradisca.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1911-cisleithanian-legislative-election] Ran as the Yugoslavian Social Democratic Party in Carniola.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1921-italian-general-election] General elections were held in Italy on 15 May 1921.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1921-italian-general-election] It was the first election in which the recently acquired regions of Trentino-Alto Adige, Venezia Giulia, Zara and Lagosta island elected deputies, many of whom were from the Germanic and South Slavic ethnic groups.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1921-italian-general-election] The 1921 election was the last free election before Benito Mussolini's fascist coup d'état.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1921-italian-general-election] From 1919 to 1920, Italy was shocked by a period of intense social conflict following the First World War known as the *Biennio Rosso* (Red Biennium).
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1921-italian-general-election] The revolutionary period was followed by the violent reaction of the Fascist Blackshirt militia and eventually by the March on Rome of Benito Mussolini in 1922.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1921-italian-general-election] The Biennio Rosso took place in a context of economic crisis at the end of the war, with high unemployment and political instability.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1921-italian-general-election] It was characterized by mass strikes, worker manifestations as well as self-management experiments through land and factories occupations.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1921-italian-general-election] In Turin and Milan, workers councils were formed and many factory occupations took place under the leadership of anarcho-syndicalists.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1921-italian-general-election] The agitations also extended to the agricultural areas of the Po Valley and were accompanied by peasant strikes, rural unrests and guerrilla conflicts between left-wing and right-wing militias.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1921-italian-general-election] In the general election of 1921, the Liberal governing coalition, strengthened by the joining of Fascist candidates in the National Bloc (33 of whom were elected deputies), came short of a majority.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1921-italian-general-election] The Italian Socialist Party, weakened by the split of the Communist Party of Italy, lost many votes and seats, while the Italian People's Party was steady around 20%.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] General elections were held in Italy on 6 April 1924 to elect the members of the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] Mussolini's National List (an alliance of fascists and a few liberal political parties) used intimidation tactics against voters, resulting in a landslide victory and a subsequent two-thirds majority.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] This was the country's last multi-party election until the 1946 Italian general election.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] On 22 October 1922 Benito Mussolini, the leader of the National Fascist Party, attempted a coup d'état (titled by the Fascist propaganda as the March on Rome) in which around 30,000 Italian fascists took part.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] Generals Gustavo Fara and Sante Ceccherini assisted to the preparations of the March of 18 October.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] Other organizers of the march included the Marquis Dino Perrone Compagni and Ulisse Igliori.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] On 24 October 1922 Mussolini declared before 60,000 people at the Fascist Congress in Naples: "Our program is simple: we want to rule Italy." The Blackshirts occupied some strategic points of the country and began to move on the capital.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] On 26 October, former Prime Minister of Italy, Antonio Salandra, warned the incumbent Prime Minister Luigi Facta that Mussolini was demanding his resignation and that he was preparing to march on Rome.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] Facta did not believe Salandra and thought that Mussolini would govern quietly at his side.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] To meet the threat posed by the bands of Fascist troops now gathering outside Rome, Facta (who had resigned but continued to hold power) ordered a state of siege for Rome.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] Having had previous conversations with King Victor Emmanuel III about the repression of Fascist violence, he was sure the King would agree.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] Instead, the King refused to sign the military order.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] On 28 October, the King handed power to Mussolini, who was supported by the military, the business class, and political right.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] While the march itself was composed of fewer than 30,000 men, the King feared a civil war as he did not consider the Facta's government strong enough, and Fascism was no longer seen as a threat to the establishment.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] Mussolini was asked to form his cabinet on 29 October while some 25,000 Blackshirts were parading in Rome.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] The March on Rome was not the conquest of power which Fascism later celebrated but rather the precipitating force behind a transfer of power within the framework of the constitution.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] This transition was made possible by the surrender of public authorities in the face of Fascist intimidation.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] Many business and financial leaders believed it would be possible to manipulate Mussolini, whose early speeches and policies emphasized free market and *laissez-faire* economics.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] While Mussolini appointed an economic liberal minister to the economy, this changed as the Great Depression affected Italy along with the rest of the world starting in 1929, and Mussolini responded to it by increasing the role of the state in the economy to avoid a banking crisis.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] Back in October 1922, even though the coup failed in giving power directly to the Fascist party, it nonetheless resulted in a parallel agreement between Mussolini and the King that made Mussolini the head of the Italian government.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] A few weeks after the election, Giacomo Matteotti, the leader of the Unitary Socialist Party, requested during his speech in front of the Parliament that the elections be annulled because of the irregularities.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] On June 10, Matteotti was assassinated by the Blackshirts and his murder provoked a momentary crisis in the Mussolini government.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] The opposition parties responded weakly or were generally unresponsive.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] Many of the socialists, liberals, and moderates boycotted Parliament in the Aventine Secession, hoping to force the King to dismiss Mussolini.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] On 31 December 1924 Blackshirt leaders met with Mussolini and gave him an ultimatum—crush the opposition or they would do so without him.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] Fearing a revolt by his own militants, he decided to drop all trappings of democracy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] On 3 January 1925, Mussolini made a truculent speech before the Chamber of Deputies in which he took responsibility for *squadristi* violence but did not mention the assassination of Matteotti.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] This speech usually is taken as the beginning of the Fascist dictatorship because it was followed by several laws restricting or canceling common democratic liberties, all rubber-stamped by a Fascist-controlled Parliament.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] This was the first and only multi-party general election held under the terms of the Acerbo Law.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] The Acerbo Law had been adopted by Parliament in November 1923 and stated that the party gaining the largest share of the votes—provided they had gained at least 25 percent of the votes—gained two-thirds of the seats in parliament.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] The remaining third was shared amongst the other parties through proportional representation.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] Only men were eligible to vote in this election.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1924-italian-general-election] NCOs and soldiers of military bodies (such as the Italian Army and Navy) were temporarily stripped of their right to vote.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] An institutional referendum (Italian: *referendum istituzionale*, or *referendum sulla forma istituzionale dello Stato*) was held by universal suffrage in the Kingdom of Italy on 2 June 1946, a key event of contemporary Italian history.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Until 1946, Italy was a kingdom ruled by the House of Savoy, reigning since the unification of Italy in 1861 and previously rulers of the Kingdom of Sardinia.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In 1922, the rise of Benito Mussolini and the creation of the Fascist regime in Italy, which eventually resulted in engaging the country in World War II alongside Nazi Germany, considerably weakened the role of the royal house.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Following the Italian Civil War and the Liberation of Italy from Axis troops in 1945, a popular referendum on the institutional form of the state was called the next year and resulted in voters choosing the replacement of the monarchy with a republic.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The 1946 Italian general election to elect the Constituent Assembly of Italy was held on the same day.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] As with the simultaneous Constituent Assembly elections, the referendum was not held in the Julian March, in the province of Zara or the province of Bolzano, which were still under occupation by Allied forces pending a final settlement of the status of the territories.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The results were proclaimed by the Supreme Court of Cassation on 10 June 1946: 12,717,923 citizens in favor of the republic and 10,719,284 citizens in favor of the monarchy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The event is commemorated annually by the *Festa della Repubblica*.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] With the entry into force of the new Constitution of the Italian Republic, on 1 January 1948, Enrico De Nicola became the first to assume the functions of president of Italy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] It marked the first time that most of the Italian Peninsula was under a single republican government since the fall of the Roman Republic.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In the history of Italy there are several so-called "republican" governments that have followed one another over time.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Examples are the ancient Roman Republic and the medieval maritime republics.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] From Cicero to Niccolò Machiavelli, Italian philosophers have imagined the foundations of political science and republicanism.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] But it was Giuseppe Mazzini who revived the republican idea in Italy in the 19th century.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] An Italian nationalist in the historical radical tradition and a proponent of a republicanism of social-democratic inspiration, Mazzini helped define the modern European movement for popular democracy in a republican state.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Mazzini formulated a concept known as "thought and action" in which thought and action must be joined and every thought must be followed by action, therefore rejecting intellectualism and the notion of divorcing theory from practice.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The foundation of the Young Italy constitutes a key moment of the Italian Risorgimento and this republican program precedes in time the proposals for the unification of Italy of Vincenzo Gioberti and Cesare Balbo, aimed at reunifying the Italian territory under the presidency of the Pope.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Subsequently, the philosopher Carlo Cattaneo promoted a secular and republican Italy in the extension of Mazzini's ideas, but organized as a federal republic.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The political projects of Mazzini and Cattaneo were thwarted by the action of the Piedmontese Prime Minister Camillo Benso, Count of Cavour, and Giuseppe Garibaldi.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The latter set aside his republican ideas to favor Italian unity.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] After having obtained the conquest of the whole of southern Italy during the Expedition of the Thousand, Garibaldi handed over the conquered territories to the king of Sardinia Victor Emmanuel II, which were annexed to the Kingdom of Sardinia after a plebiscite.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] This earned him heavy criticism from numerous republicans who accused him of treason.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] While a laborious administrative unification began, a first Italian parliament was elected and, on 17 March 1861, Victor Emmanuel II was proclaimed king of Italy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] From 1861 to 1946, Italy was a constitutional monarchy founded on the Albertine Statute, named after the king who promulgated it in 1848, Charles Albert of Sardinia.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The parliament included a Senate, whose members were appointed by the king, and a Chamber of Deputies, elected by census vote.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In 1861 only 2% of Italians had the right to vote.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In the political panorama of the time there was a republican political movement which had its martyrs, such as the soldier Pietro Barsanti.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Barsanti was a supporter of republican ideas, and was a soldier in the Royal Italian Army with the rank of corporal.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] He was sentenced to death and shot in 1870 for having favored an insurrectional attempt against the Savoy monarchy and is therefore considered the first martyr of the modern Italian Republic and a symbol of republican ideals in Italy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The balance of power between the Chamber and Senate initially shifted in favor of the Senate, composed mainly of nobles and industrial figures.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Little by little, the Chamber of Deputies took on more and more importance with the evolution of the bourgeoisie and the large landowners, concerned with economic progress, but supporters of order and a certain social conservatism.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Republicans took part in the elections to the Italian Parliament, and in 1853 they formed the Action Party around Giuseppe Mazzini.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Although in exile, Mazzini was elected in 1866, but refused to take his seat in parliament.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Carlo Cattaneo was elected deputy in 1860 and 1867, but refused so as not to have to swear loyalty to the House of Savoy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The problem of the oath of loyalty to the monarchy, necessary to be elected, was the subject of controversy within the republican forces.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In 1873 Felice Cavallotti, one of the most committed Italian politicians against the monarchy, preceded his oath with a declaration in which he reaffirmed his republican beliefs.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In 1882, a new electoral law lowered the census limit for voting rights, increasing the number of voters to over two million, equal to 7% of the population.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In the same year the Italian Workers' Party was created, which in 1895 became the Italian Socialist Party.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In 1895 the intransigent republicans agreed to participate in the political life of the Kingdom, establishing the Italian Republican Party.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Two years later, the far left reached its historical maximum level in Parliament with 81 deputies, for the three radical-democratic, socialist components and Republican.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] With the death of Felice Cavallotti in 1898, the radical left gave up on posing the institutional problem.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In Italian politics, the socialist party progressively divided into two tendencies: a maximalist one, led among others by Arturo Labriola and Enrico Ferri, and supporting the use of strikes; the other, reformist and pro-government, was led by Filippo Turati.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] A nationalist movement emerged, led in particular by Enrico Corradini, as well as a Catholic social and democratic movement, the National Democratic League, led by Romolo Murri.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In 1904, Pope Pius X authorized Catholics to participate individually in political life, but in 1909 he condemned the National Democratic League created by Romolo Murri, who was excommunicated.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Finally, a law of 3 June 1912 marked Italy's evolution towards a certain political liberalism by establishing universal male suffrage.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In 1914, at the outbreak of World War I, Italy began to be counted among the world's liberal democracies.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] After World War I, Italian political life was animated by four great movements.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Two of these movements were in favor of democratic development within the framework of existing monarchical institutions: the reformist socialists and the Italian People's Party.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Two other movements challenged these institutions: the Republican Party on the one hand, and the maximalist socialists.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In the 1919 elections, the parties most imbued with republican ideology (the maximalist socialists and the Republican Party) won, obtaining 165 out of 508 seats in the Chamber of Deputies.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In the 1921 elections, after the foundation of the Italian Communist Party, the three parties republican, maximalist socialist and communist obtained 145 deputies out of 535.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Overall, at the beginning of the interwar period, less than 30% of those elected were in favor of the establishment of a republican regime.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In this context, the rise of Benito Mussolini's fascist movement was based on the bitterness generated by the "mutilated victory", the fear of social unrest and the rejection of revolutionary, republican and Marxist ideology.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The liberal political system and part of the aristocracy chose to erect fascism as a bulwark against, in their way of seeing, these dangers.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In October 1922, the nomination of Benito Mussolini as prime minister by King Victor Emmanuel III, following the march on Rome, paved the way for the establishment of the dictatorship.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Albertine Statute was progressively emptied of its content.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Parliament was subject to the will of the new government.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 27 June 1924, 127 deputies left Parliament and retreated to the Aventine Hill, a clumsy maneuver which, in effect, left the field open to the fascists.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] They then had the fate of Italy in their hands for two decades.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Not only did Victor Emmanuel III appeal to Mussolini to form the government in 1922 and allow him to proceed with the domestication of Parliament, but he did not even draw the consequences of the assassination of Giacomo Matteotti in 1924.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] He accepted the title of emperor in 1936 at the end of Second Italo-Ethiopian War, then the alliance with Nazi Germany and Italy's entry into World War II on 10 June 1940.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] With the implementation of fascist laws (Royal Decree of 6 November 1926), all political parties operating on Italian territory were dissolved, with the exception of the National Fascist Party.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Some of these parties expatriated and reconstituted themselves abroad, especially in France.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Some movements remained outside, including the Italian Communist Party, the popular Catholic movement and other liberal movements.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] This coalition dissolved on 5 May 1934 and, in August of the same year, the pact of unity of action was signed between the Italian Socialist Party and the Italian Communist Party.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In the meantime, in Italy, clandestine anti-fascist nuclei were formed, in particular in Milan with Ferruccio Parri and in Florence with Riccardo Bauer.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Under the impetus of these groups, the Action Party, Mazzini's former republican party, was re-established.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Between the end of 1942 and the beginning of 1943, Alcide De Gasperi wrote *The reconstructive ideas of Christian Democracy*, which laid the foundations of the new Catholic-inspired party, the Christian Democracy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] It brought together the veterans of Luigi Sturzo's Italian People's Party and the young people of Catholic associations, in particular of the University Federation.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 10 July 1943, the Allies landed in Sicily in Operation Husky.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 25 July 1943, Victor Emmanuel III revoked Mussolini's mandate as prime minister and had him arrested, entrusting the government to Marshal Pietro Badoglio.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The new government contacted the Allies to reach an armistice.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] When the Armistice of Cassibile was announced on 8 September 1943, the Germans reacted by placing under their control all the part of Italian territory that still escaped the Allied advance and by disarming the Italian Royal Army.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Victor Emmanuel III and Badoglio's government fled Rome and reached Brindisi, in southern Italy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In these dramatic circumstances, in the two territories the civil administration gave way to a military and police administration.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] However, the parties that existed before fascism were reconstituted, alongside new political parties.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 9 September 1943, in Rome (still occupied by the Germans), a National Liberation Committee (CLN) was created, which brought together the parties and movements opposed to fascism and German occupation.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] It was made up of representatives of the Italian Communist Party, members of the Action Party, Christian Democrats, liberals, socialists and progressive democrats.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The patriotic war of liberation led by the National Liberation Committee was also, for a significant part of its supporters, a war of social liberation, a war against a collaborationist elite.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] However, the Americans and English, anxious to prepare for the post-war period, facilitated the entry into German-occupied territory of Italian democratic and republican activists aimed at counterbalancing the communist influence in the leadership of the National Liberation Committee.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] This was the case, for example, of Leo Valiani, future member of the triumvirate responsible for the partisan insurrection in Piedmont and Lombardy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 31 March 1944, in Salerno, Palmiro Togliatti, general secretary of the Italian Communist Party, called for the formation of a government of national unity and no longer required the king's abdication as a prerequisite.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] This declaration pushed the parties of the National Liberation Committee to rally around a compromise drawn up by Enrico De Nicola, president of the Chamber of Deputies until 1924, by Benedetto Croce of the liberal party and by the king's entourage.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] As foreseen in this agreement, upon the liberation of Rome, on 4 June 1944, Victor Emmanuel III proclaimed his son Umberto lieutenant general of the kingdom, and the parties took political control of the nation, even if the war continued, stabilizing on the front on the Gothic line until April 1945.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] From June 1944 to December 1945, three provisional coalition governments followed one another.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The first was led by Ivanoe Bonomi, of the Labour Democratic Party.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] His government included the anti-fascist liberals Carlo Sforza and Benedetto Croce, as well as Palmiro Togliatti.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Although temporarily put aside, the question of Italian institutions remained one of the main open political questions.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Most of the forces supporting the National Liberation Committee were openly republicans and believed that the monarchy, in particular Victor Emmanuel III, had had a responsibility in the success of the fascist movement.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The final agreement between the parties was to ask that at the end of the war, as soon as conditions were favourable, the calling of elections, an institutional referendum and the formation of a constituent assembly.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Until then, on 31 January 1945, the Council of Ministers, chaired by Ivanoe Bonomi, issued a decree which recognized women's right to vote.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Universal suffrage was thus recognized, after the vain attempts made in 1881 and 1907 by women of the various parties.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Bonomi governments (II then III) were succeeded by the Parri government in June 1945, then by the First De Gasperi government in December 1945.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The question of the future form of the state, monarchy or republic, absorbed the minds of political circles.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The majority of Christian Democratic activists, especially young people, increasingly distanced themselves from the monarchy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] During the local meetings of the leaders of this party, in Rome and Milan, motions were presented aimed at making official a political line favorable to a democratic republic.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The central political office tried to curb these pressures and maintain an intermediate position.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 16 March 1946, Prince Umberto decreed, as expected in 1944, that the question of the institutional form of the state would be decided by a referendum organized simultaneously with the election of a constituent assembly.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Supreme Court of Cassation was responsible for examining the appeals.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Its role was to be limited to observing the progress of voting operations and consolidating the bulletins issued by the offices that communicated the results in each constituency.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The counting of the ballots of the candidates for the constituent assembly had to precede that of the referendum.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] If the monarchy had won, it would have been the Constituent Assembly that would have had to choose the head of state.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Wanted by the Allies to verify that the conditions existed for voting in a country torn apart by the civil war only a few months earlier, partial municipal and provincial elections were held in March and April 1946 in half of the Italian municipalities and provinces.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] These elections, which mainly involved left-wing cities, brought out three parties, with a clear advantage for the Christian Democrats, led by Alcide De Gasperi, which exceeded the sum of votes cast for the Italian Communist Party and the Italian Socialist Party.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] After these administrative elections, the monarchists, already worried about the outcome of the referendum, became even more discouraged.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] But a political event changed the situation during the referendum campaign.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] A month before the referendum, Victor Emmanuel III abdicated in favor of his son Umberto, who was proclaimed king and took the name Umberto II.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The act of abdication, drawn up privately, is dated 9 May 1946.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] This abdication was desired by the monarchists, since the crown prince was less compromised than his father in Mussolini's rise to power and in coexistence with the fascist forces.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] It is also possible that the command of the allied forces present on Italian territory encouraged the sovereign to abdicate in favor of his son.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The former king immediately left Italy for Alexandria in Egypt.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Umberto II confirmed his promise to respect the popular decision regarding the referendum.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The representatives of the parties in favor of the Republic protested, arguing the assumption of royal powers by the lieutenant general conflicted with an article of the legislative decree of 16 March 1946 that aimed at guaranteeing institutional stability before the announcement of the results.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] For observers, the gap between republicans and monarchists was narrowing, which increased tension in the final phase of the electoral campaign.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In fact, some scuffles broke out between activists of the two sides in the tense climate.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The vote for the choice between monarchy or republic took place on 2 June and on the morning of 3 June 1946.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] After the transfer of the electoral cards from all of Italy and the minutes of the 31 constituencies to Rome, the results were expected on 8 June.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 10 June, the still provisional results were announced, and the final ones were communicated later due to missing data in some polling stations and after the examination of numerous appeals regarding the contested referendum ballots.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In fact, 21,000 disputes occurred over the referendum ballots, most of which were quickly resolved.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] However, the period of uncertainty between the end of the vote and the final official announcement of the results only strengthened tensions in the country.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In the city of Naples, in Apulia, in Calabria and in Sicily, the monarchists carried out protest demonstrations, sometimes violent.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 7 June, a monarchist student, soon transformed into a martyr, was killed.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] One of the complaints submitted to the Supreme Court of Cassation is particularly delicate.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] This controversy was over the definition of "majority".
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The monarchists believed that it was necessary to take into account not the majority of votes cast, but the "majority of electors", as an article of the electoral law provided.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The public prosecutor of the Supreme Court of Cassation, Massimo Pilotti, deemed this appeal admissible.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In his indictment Pilotti believed that the spirit and letter of the decrees as well as jurisprudence provide for the counting of voters, without excluding blank or invalid ballots.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] But the Supreme Court of Cassation ruled against him, with 12 votes against to 7.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On the one hand, it was believed that the vote, as a legal act, manifested a will and that the blank or null vote could be assimilated to the absence of expression of will.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Supreme Court of Cassation also identified another decree which specified that only "validly cast" votes should be preserved.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Supreme Court of Cassation finally announced that no law or decree dealt with the need for an absolute majority.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The final results were announced on 18 June 1946.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Voter turnout was 89%, with 54% of the votes cast for the republic and 46% for the monarchy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The analysis of the data by region showed an Italy practically divided in two: in the north the republic won with 66% of the votes cast, and the monarchy in the south with 64% of the votes.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] However, some voters were unable to vote.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Before the closure of the electoral lists in April 1945, many Italian soldiers were still outside the national territory, in detention or internment camps abroad.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] These provinces, however, were all located in the north of the country, an area where the Republican vote obtained a fairly large majority.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The conservative, rural *Mezzogiorno* (southern Italy) region voted solidly for the monarchy (63.8%) while the more urbanised and industrialised *Nord* (northern Italy) voted equally firmly for a republic (66.2%).
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The referendum was not held in the Julian March, in the province of Zara or the province of Bolzano, which were still under occupation by Allied forces pending a final settlement of the status of the territories.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] At first glance, the referendum seemed to simply divide Italy in two, between North and South, but the situation was more complex.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] For example, the districts located to the north of Rome gave the majority to the republic, while those located to the south chose the monarchy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The electoral college of Rome was very divided and gave a slight majority to the choice of the monarchic regime.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Republican choice turned into a plebiscite, with over 80% of the votes cast in the electoral college of Bologna, and even more in that of Trento.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In the South, however, the monarchist choice reached nearly 80% in the college of Naples.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] But, in other regions, the vote was very fragmented.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] There was not a total break with the past, but an interference between the two possible choices, which was expressed everywhere.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The occupation of the North by the German forces and the period of the Italian Civil War, with the fascist forces, undoubtedly favored an increase in the importance of the socialist and communist parties in this region, which were republican in tendency.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] During these dark years, the populations concerned placed part of their hopes in dreams of revolution, or at least of change.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The South, not having experienced this situation and having welcomed King Victor Emmanuel III and his government, was perhaps more wary of these parties and placed its trust in the monarchic regime, preferring continuity to the "leap into the unknown" represented by the republican form.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Furthermore, the clientelism prevalent in the South favored a vote that tended to be conservative, and therefore monarchist.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Some analysts also cite the influence of the Catholic Church or the Catholic press.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Other authors have highlighted more structural factors, such as differences in family organization or production by region.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Thus Carlo Bacetti compared, in Tuscany, the importance of metayage in the organization of work on the land, and the weight of the Communist Party in this region, which had republican tendencies.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] At the same time, republican demonstrations took place in many cities.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Milanese newspaper, *Corriere della Sera*, on Tuesday 11 June, ran the headline: "The Italian Republic is born".
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] *La Stampa*, a Turin daily newspaper, declared more soberly: "The government confirms the victory of the republicans", and completed its coverage by asking: "the question is whether the republic has been proclaimed or not".
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In Naples, a city with a population largely supportive of the monarchy, an incident occurred on 11 June.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] A procession of supporters of the monarchy advanced towards the municipal buildings and then changed objective and headed towards the headquarters of the Italian Communist Party.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The crowd saw a red flag, but also a tricolor flag from which the royal coat of arms had been cut.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Despite the presence of armored vehicles, the demonstrators attempted to storm the communist party headquarters.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Protesters and law enforcement officers exchange gunfire.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] According to the prefect's report, the demonstrators shot first.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In any case the response was deadly, with machine gun fire.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] There were nine deaths among royalist demonstrators and a large number of injuries.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Calm returned to the city only on 13 June.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On the night of 12 June, the government met at Alcide De Gasperi's invitation.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Prime Minister received a written communication from the King, in which he said he was ready to respect the verdict of the electors' vote, but adding that he would await the final declaration of the Supreme Court of Cassation.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The letter and the protests of the monarchists, like the bloody events of the day before in Naples, as well as the new demonstrations announced by the monarchists worried the ministers.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Prime Minister collected all the votes of the government members, with the exception of the liberal minister Leone Cattani.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Although some members of his entourage encouraged him to oppose this decision, the king, informed, decided to leave the country the following day, thus making a peaceful transfer of power possible, not without having denounced De Gasperi's "revolutionary gesture".
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] He went into exile in Cascais, Portugal.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On the same day as the former king's departure, the flag of Italy with the Savoy coat of arms in the centre was lowered from the Quirinal Palace.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Italian flag was modified with the decree of the president of the Council of Ministers No.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Compared to the monarchic banner, the Savoy coat of arms was eliminated.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The Republican tricolour was then officially and solemnly delivered to the Italian military corps on 4 November 1947 on the occasion of National Unity and Armed Forces Day.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The universally adopted ratio is 2:3, while the war flag is squared (1:1).
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Each *comune* also has a *gonfalone* bearing its coat of arms.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 27 May 1949, a law was passed that described and regulated the way the flag was displayed outside public buildings and during national holidays.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] After the birth of the Italian Republic, "La leggenda del Piave" was temporarily chosen as the provisional national anthem, which replaced "Marcia Reale", the national anthem of the Kingdom of Italy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The political class of the time then approved the proposal of the War Minister Cipriano Facchinetti, who foresaw the adoption of "Il Canto degli Italiani" as a provisional anthem of the State.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] "Il Canto degli Italiani" was therefore chosen, on 12 October 1946, as the provisional national anthem, a role that it later preserved while remaining the de facto anthem of the Italian Republic.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Over the decades there were several unsuccessful attempts to make it the official national anthem, until it finally gained official status on 4 December 2017.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 18 June 1946 at 6 pm, in the Sala della Lupa of Palazzo Montecitorio in Rome, the Supreme Court of Cassation proceeded to proclaim the results of the referendum, without accompanying this formalization with reservations as it had done previously.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In the first session of the Constituent Assembly, on 28 June 1946, Enrico De Nicola was elected provisional head of the State, in the first round with 396 votes out of 501.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] In addition to his personal qualities, the choice of a man born in Naples and long monarchic history, it was a sign of pacification and union towards the populations of southern Italy, in this accelerated transition towards the Republic.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] He was initially only provisional head of state and not president of Italy, since the latter did not yet have a constitution.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Alcide De Gasperi resigned and then regained the task of forming a new government, thus becoming the last Prime Minister of the monarchic era and the first of republican Italy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On 1 January 1948, the Republican Constitution came into force, the content of which was discussed within the Constituent Assembly.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] It proclaims in particular that "Italy is a democratic republic founded on labour" and that "the former kings of the House of Savoy, their wives and their male descendants are prohibited from entering and staying in the national territory".
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Enrico De Nicola then assumed the title of President of Italy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The validity of the provision that prohibited the entry in Italy of some members of the House of Savoy ceased with the entry into force of the Constitutional Law of 23 October 2002, No.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] 1, after a debate in parliament and in the country that lasted many years and Vittorio Emanuele, Prince of Naples, son of King Umberto II, was able to enter Italy with his family already in the following December for a short visit.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The former queen Marie-José had already been authorized to return to Italy in 1987 since, with the death of her husband Umberto II and having become a widow, her status as "spouse" was recognized as having ceased.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The photo, which later became a "symbol" of the celebrations for the outcome of the referendum, portrays the face of a young woman emerging from a copy of *Il Corriere della Sera* of 6 June 1946 with the title «*È nata la Repubblica Italiana*» ("The Italian Republic is born").
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The symbolic photo of the birth of the Republic was taken by Federico Patellani for the weekly *Tempo* (n.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] 22, 15–22 June 1946) as part of a photo shoot celebrating the Republic and the new role of women; it was also featured on the front page of the *Il Corriere della Sera* itself and was later reused in many campaigns and posters.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Only in 2016 was the woman identified as Anna Iberti (1922–1997).
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] After the playing of the National Anthem *Il Canto degli Italiani*, the Frecce Tricolori cross the skies of Rome.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] It is tradition, for the members of the Italian government and for the presidents of the two chambers of parliament, to have pinned on their jacket, during the whole ceremony, an Italian tricolor cockade.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Following the anthem, the military parade begins, which the ground columns of military personnel saluting the President with eyes left or right with their colours dipped as they march past the dais.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Mobile column crew contingent colour guards perform the salute in a like manner.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] The military parade also includes some military delegations from the United Nations, NATO, the European Union and representatives of multinational departments with an Italian component.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] On the holiday, at the Quirinale Palace, the Changing of the Guard with the Corazzieri Regiment and the Fanfare of the Carabinieri Cavalry Regiment in high uniform is carried out in solemn form.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] This solemn rite is only performed on two other occasions, during the celebrations of the Tricolour Day (7 January) and the National Unity and Armed Forces Day (4 November).
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Official ceremonies are held throughout the national territory.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Among them are the traditional receptions organized by each prefecture for the local authorities, which are preceded by solemn public demonstrations with reduced military parades that have been reviewed by the prefect in his capacity as the highest governmental authority in the province.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Similar ceremonies are also organized by the Regions and Municipalities.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] All over the world, Italian embassies organize ceremonies to which the Heads of State of the host country are invited.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-constitutional-referendum] Greetings from the other Heads of State reach the President of Italy from all over the world.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-general-election] General elections were held in Italy on Sunday 2 and also on Monday 3 June (but until noon) 1946.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-general-election] They were the first after World War II and elected 556 deputies to the Constituent Assembly.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-general-election] Theoretically, a total of 573 deputies were to be elected, but the election did not take place in the Julian March and in South Tyrol, which were under military occupation by the United Nations.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-general-election] For the first time, Italian women were allowed to vote in a national election and run for a seat in the Constituent Assembly.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-general-election] This election was held concurrently with the 1946 Italian institutional referendum on the abolition of the monarchy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-general-election] To emphasise the restoration of democracy after the fascist era, a pure party-list proportional representation was chosen.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-general-election] Italian provinces were united in 31 constituencies, each electing a group of candidates.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-general-election] At constituency level, seats were divided between open lists using the largest remainder method with the Imperiali quota.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-general-election] Remaining votes and seats were transferred at national level, where special closed lists of national leaders received the last seats using the Hare quota.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-general-election] At the end of World War II, Italy was governed under transitional laws as a result of agreements between the National Liberation Committee (CLN) and the royal Lieutenant General of the Realm Umberto II of Italy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-general-election] As no democratic elections had taken place for more than 20 years, legislative power was given to the government but, after the first election, the Italian Council of Ministers would have to receive a vote of confidence by the new Constituent Assembly.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-general-election] The three main contestants were Christian Democracy and the Italian Socialist Party, which had both received popular support before the fascist era, and the Italian Communist Party, which had strengthened itself with the armed struggle against Nazism and fascism during the war.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-general-election] The Italian Liberal Party, heir of the pre-fascist and conservative ruling class, proposed an alliance called National Democratic Union.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-general-election] Monarchists groups created the National Bloc of Freedom, while the liberal socialist Action Party and Labour Democratic Party hoped to maximize the positive image of the governments that they ruled in the National Liberation Committee.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-general-election] The election gave a large majority to the government formed by the three leaders of the CLN, which was briefly joined by the Republican Party after the exile of Umberto II.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-general-election] Together with the election, a constitutional referendum took place.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-general-election] Italian electors chose whether to continue the reign of Umberto II of Italy or turn Italy into a republic.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1946-italian-general-election] While all regions of northern Italy as far as Tuscany and Marches gave a majority to the republic, all regions of southern Italy to Lazio and Abruzzo voted to maintain the monarchy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In late February 1948, the Communist Party of Czechoslovakia (KSČ), with Soviet backing, assumed undisputed control over the government of Czechoslovakia through a coup d'état.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] It marked the beginning of four decades of the party's rule in the country.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The KSČ enjoyed a period of popularity following the reestablishment of pre-war Czechoslovakia.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] After a successful performance during the 1946 parliamentary election, party leader Klement Gottwald became prime minister of a coalition government at the behest of President Edvard Beneš.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] By summer 1947, however, the KSČ's popularity had significantly dwindled, and the party was expected to be soundly defeated in the May 1948 elections.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] This, along with the electoral failures of the French and Italian communist parties, prompted Joseph Stalin to harden his approach and order Gottwald to seize power.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] On 21 February 1948, twelve non-Communist ministers resigned in protest.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] They objected to Gottwald's refusal to stop packing the police with Communists, and believed that Gottwald would give way.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Instead, he threatened a general strike unless Beneš appointed a Communist-dominated government.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Armed Communist militia and police took over Prague and mass demonstrations were mounted.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] On 25 February, Beneš, fearing civil war and Soviet intervention, capitulated and allowed the formation of a new government in accordance with KSČ demands.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] While ostensibly a coalition, it was dominated by Communists and fellow travellers.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The Communists quickly consolidated their power following the coup.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The National Assembly approved a new constitution on 9 May, declaring Czechoslovakia a "people's democratic state".
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The 30 May elections, in which voters were presented with a single list of candidates, all but confirmed the Communist victory.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Beneš resigned on 2 June and was succeeded by Gottwald as president.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The coup's significance extended well beyond the state's boundaries as it was a clear marker along the already well-advanced road to full-fledged Cold War.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In the aftermath of World War II, the Communist Party of Czechoslovakia (KSČ) was in a favorable position.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Moreover, the Soviets viewed the country as a strategic prize: it bordered West Germany and boasted uranium deposits around Jáchymov.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] During the early postwar period, working with the other parties in a coalition called the National Front, the Communists kept up the appearance of being willing to work within the system.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Thus, in the 1946 election, the KSČ and KSS won 38% of the vote.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] This was the best-ever performance by a European Communist party in a free election, and was far more than the 22% won by their Hungarian counterparts the following year in the only other free and fair postwar election in the Soviet area of influence.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] President Edvard Beneš, not himself a Communist but very amenable to cooperation with the Soviets, and who hoped for restraint by the Allied powers, thus invited Gottwald to be prime minister.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] However, by the summer of 1947 the KSČ had alienated whole blocs of potential voters.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The activities of the police—headed by Interior Minister Václav Nosek, a Communist—were acutely offensive to many citizens; farmers objected to talk of collectivization, and some workers were angry at Communist demands that they increase output without being given higher wages.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The general expectation was that the Communists would be soundly defeated in the May 1948 elections.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] That notion would be reinforced during the Prague Spring, when party archives were opened and showed that Stalin gave up the whole idea of a parliamentary path for Czechoslovakia when the Communist parties of France and Italy failed to achieve power in 1947 and 1948.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The KSČ's number-two leader, general secretary Rudolf Slánský, represented the KSČ at the meeting.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] He returned to Prague with a plan for the final seizure of power.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Slánský remarked, "as in the international field, we have gone on the offensive on the domestic front as well." The KSČ pursued a two-pronged strategy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The party knew it had to maintain the façade of working within the electoral political system and was aware that a revolutionary coup would be unacceptable.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] It desired to gain an absolute majority at elections scheduled for 1948, but the fracturing of the left-wing coalition made this unrealistic.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] This pushed the party into extra-parliamentary action.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The organization of "spontaneous" demonstrations to "express the will of the people" and continuous visits to parliament by workers' delegations were meant to ensure "mobilization of the masses".
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] During the winter of 1947–48, both in the cabinet and in parliament tension between the Communists and their opponents led to increasingly bitter conflict.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Matters came to a head in February 1948, when Nosek illegally extended his powers by attempting to purge remaining non-Communist elements in the National Police Force.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The security apparatus and police were being transformed into instruments of the KSČ, and consequently, according to John Grenville, endangering basic civic freedoms.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] On 12 February, the non-Communists in the cabinet demanded punishment for the offending Communists in the government and an end to their supposed subversion.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Nosek, backed by Gottwald, refused to yield.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] He and his fellow Communists threatened to use force and, in order to avoid defeat in parliament, mobilised groups of their supporters in the country.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] On 21 February, twelve non-Communist ministers resigned in protest after Nosek refused to reinstate eight non-Communist senior police officers despite a majority vote of the cabinet in favour of doing so.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Most of the ministers remained at their posts, with Social Democratic leader Zdeněk Fierlinger making no secret of his support for the Communists.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The non-Communists assumed that Beneš would refuse to accept their resignations, keeping them in a caretaker government and in the process embarrassing the Communists enough to make them yield.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Beneš initially insisted that no new government could be formed which did not include ministers from the non-Communist parties.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] However, an atmosphere of mounting tension, coupled with massive Communist-led demonstrations occurring throughout the country, convinced Beneš to remain neutral over the issue, for fear the KSČ foment an insurrection and give the Red Army a pretext to invade the country and restore order.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In Grenville's opinion, had Beneš held his line, the Communists would not have been able to form a government.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The historian believed there could have been only two non-violent means of resolving the crisis—give way to the non-Communists or risk defeat in early elections which the KSČ would not have had time to rig.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The non-Communists saw this as a moment of opportunity, needing to act quickly before the Communists had total control over the police and threatened the electoral process.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] At the same time, the non-Communist ministers seemed to behave as if this was just an old-fashioned pre-1939 governmental crisis.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] They did not know that the Communists were mobilizing from below to take complete power.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Soviet deputy foreign minister Valerian Zorin, who had been his country's ambassador to Czechoslovakia from 1945 to 1947, returned to Prague to help with the final arrangements for the coup.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Armed militia and police took over Prague, Communist demonstrations were mounted and an anti-Communist student demonstration was broken up.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The ministries of the non-Communist ministers were occupied, civil servants dismissed and the ministers prevented from entering their own ministries.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The army, under the direction of Defence Minister Ludvík Svoboda, who was formally non-partisan but had facilitated Communist infiltration into the officer corps, was confined to barracks and did not interfere.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Communist "Action Committees" and trade union militias were quickly set up, armed, and sent into the streets, as well as being prepared to carry through a purge of anti-Communists.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In a speech before 100,000 of these people, Gottwald threatened a general strike unless Beneš agreed to form a new Communist-dominated government.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Zorin at one point offered the services of the Red Army, camped on the country's borders.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] However, Gottwald declined the offer, believing that the threat of violence combined with heavy political pressure would be enough to force Beneš to surrender.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] As he said after the coup, Beneš "knows what strength is, and this led him to evaluate this [situation] realistically".
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Additionally, according to historian Igor Lukes, Beneš had been in poor health since 1945, and by 1948 was "a shell of a man" who did not have the emotional or physical stamina to hold out against the "rough, rough players" of the KSČ.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] On 25 February 1948, Beneš, fearful of civil war and Soviet intervention, capitulated.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] He accepted the resignations of the non-Communist ministers and appointed a new government in accordance with KSČ demands.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Gottwald continued as prime minister of a new government comprising 25 members–13 Communists and 12 non-Communists (nine members from non-Communist parties and three independents).
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In truth, the new government was dominated by Communists and pro-Moscow Social Democrats.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The Social Democrats' leader, Fierlinger, had been a proponent of closer ties with the Communists for some time; as mentioned above, he openly sided with the Communists during the dispute.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Members of the People's, Czech National Social Party and Slovak Democratic parties still figured, so the government was still nominally a coalition.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] However, this was no longer a coalition in any real sense of the term.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The other parties had been taken over by fellow travellers who were loyal partners of the Communists, and ministers using these labels were handpicked by the Communists.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The only senior minister who was neither a Communist nor a fellow traveller was Foreign Minister Jan Masaryk, who was however found dead two weeks later outside a third-floor window.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Some friends and admirers believed Masaryk committed suicide out of despair.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] However, there was longstanding Western suspicion was that he had actually been thrown to his death, which remains to this day, with an investigation closed in 2021 ruling murder, accident, or suicide all possible.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Following the coup, the Communists moved quickly to consolidate their power.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Thousands were fired and hundreds were arrested.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Thousands fled the country to avoid living under Communism.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The National Assembly, freely elected two years earlier, quickly fell into line and gave Gottwald's revamped government a vote of confidence in March.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The 230–0 result was unanimous, although nine MPs had resigned following the coup.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] On 9 May, a new constitution was approved by parliament, which declared Czechoslovakia a "people's democratic state." Although it was not a completely Communist document (indeed, the KSČ was not even mentioned), it was close enough to the Soviet model that Beneš refused to sign it.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] At the 30 May elections, voters were presented with a single list from the National Front, which officially won 89.2% of the vote; within the National Front list, the Communists had an absolute majority of 214 seats (160 for the main party and 54 for the Slovak branch).
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] This majority grew even larger when the Social Democrats merged with the Communists later in the year.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Practically all non-Communist parties that had participated in the 1946 election were also represented within the National Front list and thus received parliamentary seats.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] However, by this time they were now almost completely subservient to the Communists, and the few independent-minded members of those parties were either in prison or in exile.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The National Front was converted into a broad patriotic organisation dominated by the Communists, and no political group outside it was allowed to exist.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Consumed by these events, Beneš resigned on 2 June and was succeeded by Gottwald twelve days later.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Beneš died in September, bringing a symbolic close to the sequence of events, and was buried before an enormous and silent throng come to mourn the passing of a popular leader and of the democracy he had come to represent.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Czechoslovakia was ruled by a victorious Communist Party of Czechoslovakia until the Velvet Revolution of 1989.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] More immediately, the coup became synonymous with the Cold War.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The loss of the last remaining liberal democracy in Eastern Europe came as a profound shock to millions in the West.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] For the second time in a decade, Western eyes saw Czechoslovak independence and democracy snuffed out by a foreign totalitarian dictatorship intent on dominating the small country (though unlike in 1938–39, the KSČ did most of the "dirty work").
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Because its impact was equally profound in Western Europe as in the United States, it helped unify Western countries against the Communist bloc.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] It gave an air of prescience to the French and Italian governments for having forced their local Communists out of their governments a year earlier.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Additionally, it finally discredited Soviet moves to prevent the formation of a West German state and accelerated the construction of a West European alliance, the Treaty of Brussels, the following month; mutual security was the new watchword.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] By early March, even a previously wavering France was demanding a concrete military alliance with definite promises to help in certain circumstances.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] From the Soviet's point of view, the coup could not have come at a worse time.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The government crisis in Prague lasted from 20 to 27 February, just when Western foreign ministers were meeting in London.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] From the West's perspective, the coup was an example of Communism in its most unacceptable form; the USSR seemed to the West bent on ruthless expansion and the suppression of freedom.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The coup's impact in the United States was immediate.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Opposition towards the Marshall Plan had developed in the United States Congress, but a shocked and aroused public opinion overwhelmed this, and Congress promptly approved over US$5 billion for the first year of the European Recovery Program.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Until the Czech coup, the emphasis in Washington had been on economic containment of Communism, primarily through the Truman Doctrine and the Marshall Plan and a heavy reliance on atomic power as a shield to support it.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Truman understood that in 1946 and 1947 the American people were not prepared for a massive conventional arms buildup or a confrontation with the Soviet Union.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] He was reluctant to increase the military budget dramatically and instead chose a gradual and balanced buildup.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Expecting to spend large amounts on the Marshall Plan, he sought to keep the annual defence budget below $15 billion.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] However, the coup served to expose the limitations of U.S. conventional forces and its over-reliance on atomic power.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] At the time of the Prague crisis, roughly ten ill-equipped and poorly trained U.S. and West European divisions faced over thirty Soviet divisions.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] When taking into account Defense Department complaints that the U.S. atomic arsenal and the air power to use it were starkly inadequate, it became clear that the U.S. lacked a credible military deterrent in Europe.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The Czechoslovak coup changed the whole tone of the debate on the U.S. military budget.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] It helped spark a new round of Pentagon lobbying for a substantial rise in the military budget, while the NSC called for "a worldwide counter-offensive" against the Soviet bloc, including U.S. military aid to the Western European Union.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Truman responded to the crisis with a grim nationwide radio address on 17 March calling for a renewal of selective service, which had been allowed to lapse the previous year.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] He also sought congressional approval for a programme of Universal Military Training (UMT).
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] He aimed to send a signal of determination to the Soviet Union that U.S. military posture was strong and that the country with this expansion of military preparedness was also prepared in the future to rearm massively if necessary.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Congress rejected UMT, but did vote to resume selective service, and voted the money for a seventy-group air force, 25% larger than the official request.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Nevertheless, the change in American foreign policy in response to the crisis-like atmosphere of early 1948 was more symbolic than real.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] American willingness to consult on new security arrangements for Europe was the product of neither a changed estimate of Soviet intentions nor a readiness to take on a larger share of the burden of defending Western Europe.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Rather, it was a tactical maneuver intended to mitigate the effect of the coup in Czechoslovakia and the brief but intense war scare that followed.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] As a result, a series of quick fixes followed to ensure that American forces would not be caught completely off guard in the event of war.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] More important was the sensitivity with which American officials now treated the nervousness of their European counterparts; the Americans now became more willing to take steps to boost morale in Europe and ease the now-widespread anxieties there.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The coup and the Berlin Blockade that June made clear that constant reassurance was needed to bind the Europeans to the U.S. system; hence, the remobilization of U.S. armed forces began.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Indeed, the fear of war between the Soviets and the West reached a high point after the coup.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Clay sent an alarming telegram from Berlin that advised of its likelihood: "Within the last few weeks, I have felt a subtle change in Soviet attitude which I cannot define but which now gives me a feeling that it may come with dramatic suddenness".
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] General Omar Bradley later wrote that when he read Clay's "lugubrious assessment" in Washington he was "lifted right out of [his] chair", and George F.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Kennan wrote that the coup and the telegram had combined to create "a real war scare" where "the military and the intelligence fraternity" had "overreacted in the most deplorable way".
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Only a week later, the Joint Chiefs of Staff recommended rearmament and a restoration of the draft.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In fact, Clay's warning had more to do with a request by Army director of intelligence Lt.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Stephen Chamberlain for material that would persuade Congress to spend more on military readiness than with any hard evidence of Soviet intent to launch a war in Europe.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Amidst the general alarm, more sanguine voices were also raised.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The Truman Administration had months earlier written off Czechoslovakia as little more than a Soviet satellite; in November 1947 U.S.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Marshall told a cabinet meeting that the Soviets would probably soon consolidate their hold on Eastern Europe by clamping down on Czechoslovakia as a "purely defensive move", and Kennan cabled from Manila that the Soviets seemed to be consolidating their defences, not preparing for aggression.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] He later wrote that the Prague coup and the Berlin Blockade were "defensive reactions" to the Marshall Plan's initial successes and to the Western decision to press for an independent West German state.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] This view of the event sees Truman's reaction as him seizing on a necessary crisis to sell the Marshall Plan and the rearmament programme the Pentagon had long been pushing.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Marshall's own reaction was that "in so far as international affairs are concerned, a seizure of power by the Communist Party in Czechoslovakia would not materially alter...the situation which has existed in the last three years".
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Hillenkoetter had also written to Truman that "the timing of the coup in Czechoslovakia was forced upon the Kremlin when the non-Communists took action endangering Communist control of the police.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] A Communist victory in the May elections would have been impossible without such control".
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In Italy, elections were scheduled for 18 April and the Communist-dominated Popular Democratic Front stood a realistic chance of victory.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In the hysteria and foreboding that gripped Western circles following the Czech coup, it was concluded that similar tactics could be employed in Italy, whose citizens might not even have a chance to vote.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] British Foreign Minister Ernest Bevin and the British Cabinet saw the cooperation between the two leading parties of the Italian left in almost apocalyptic terms, believing that once the Italian Communist Party (PCI) won power it would marginalise any moderating influence from the socialists.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Bevin immediately concluded that the "forces of democratic Socialism" must be strengthened in Italy, and that Britain must support the Christian Democrats, despite all of their faults.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The Italian foreign minister, despite his alarm over the coup's timing, remained optimistic, assuring Bevin (who saw Italy as "the immediate danger spot") that the army and police were in excellent shape and that the coup would have an adverse effect, turning swing voters away from the socialists.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Kennan cabled to suggest the PCI should be outlawed and the U.S. should intervene militarily in the likely event of a civil war, but he quickly softened his line.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] However, the coup was one of several factors that led a strong plurality of voters to vote for Christian Democracy and defeat the left.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Stalin, satisfied that America had not moved militarily after the Czech coup and unwilling to provoke war, respected the result, considering Italy a Western country.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In France, interesting political currents were also set in motion.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The United States was still pushing the French government to support German rehabilitation.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] In the aftermath of the coup, foreign minister Georges Bidault was afraid of stoking anti-German sentiment that the French Communist Party (PCF) could exploit and harness to instigate a coup of its own.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] At the same time, the coup had forced the hand of PCF leader Maurice Thorez, whose public remarks suggested that in the wake of a Soviet invasion, he would support the Red Army.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The Czech coup, the PCF's failed policy of sabotage and the Marshall Plan's likely passage were all beginning to sway French public opinion.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] 70% of French people now believed the U.S. would do more than any other country to help France, compared to 7% who thought the USSR would do more.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Despite French concern about Germany, it was becoming increasingly clear that the Soviet threat was greater than the German.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] France would still seek an advantageous power position vis-à-vis Germany, but it was becoming reconciled to the prospect of a rehabilitated Germany as part of postwar Europe.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] Along with passage of the Marshall Plan, the other far-reaching implication of the Czech coup for U.S. foreign policy was to heed Bevin's call for a Western defence association.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] On 26 February, Bevin again reiterated that the best way to prevent another Czechoslovakia was to evolve a joint Western military strategy, and this time he got a more receptive hearing, especially considering American anxiety over Italy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] That spring, European leaders quietly met with U.S. defence, military and diplomatic officials at the Pentagon, under Marshall's orders, exploring a framework for a new and unprecedented association for mutual defence.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/1948-czechoslovak-coup-d-état] The following year, NATO would ultimately be born out of these talks.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] De Gasperi was the last prime minister of the Kingdom of Italy, serving under both Victor Emmanuel III and Umberto II.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] He was also the first prime minister of the Italian Republic, and also briefly served as provisional head of state after the Italian people voted to end the monarchy and establish a republic.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] His eight-year term in office remains a landmark of political longevity for a leader in modern Italian politics.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] De Gasperi is the fifth longest-serving prime minister since the unification of Italy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] A devout Catholic, De Gasperi was one of the founding fathers of the European Union along with fellow Italian Altiero Spinelli.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] De Gasperi was born in 1881 in Pieve Tesino in Tyrol, now part of the Italian region of Trentino-Alto Adige, which had been part of Austria-Hungary for more than 500 years.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] His father was a local police officer of limited financial means.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] From 1896, De Gasperi was active in the Social Christian movement.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In 1900 he joined the Faculty of Literature and Philosophy in Vienna, where he played an important role in the inception of the Christian student movement.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] He was very much inspired by the *Rerum novarum* encyclical issued by Pope Leo XIII in 1891.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In 1904, he took an active part in student demonstrations in favour of an Italian-language university.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] During the inauguration of the Italian Faculty of Law in Innsbruck, he was imprisoned with a number of other protesting students, but was released after twenty days.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In 1905, De Gasperi obtained a degree in philology.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In 1905, he began to work as editor of the newspaper *La Voce Cattolica* (The Catholic Voice) which was replaced in September 1906 by *Il Trentino* and he soon became its editor.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In his newspaper, he often took positions in favour of cultural autonomy for Trentino and in defence of Italian culture in Trentino, in contrast to the Germanisation planned by the German nationalists in Tyrol.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] At the time, in disagreement with other politicians like Cesare Battisti, he did not seek unification with Italy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] From 1908 to 1912, he was vice-president and one of the three executive board members of the Banca Industriale di Trento, a local investment bank supported by the Catholic movement.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In 1911, he became a member of Parliament for the Popular Political Union of Trentino (UPPT) in the Austrian Reichsrat, a post he held for six years.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] At the beginning of World War I, he was politically neutral, sympathizing with the ultimately unsuccessful efforts of Pope Benedict XV and Karl I of Austria to obtain an honourable peace and stop the war.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In 1919, he was among the founders of the Italian People's Party (PPI), with Luigi Sturzo.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] He served as a deputy in the Italian Parliament from 1921 to 1924, a period marked by the rise of Fascism.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] He initially supported the participation of the PPI in Benito Mussolini's first government in October 1922.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The PPI split, and De Gasperi became secretary of the remaining anti-Fascist group in May 1924.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In November 1926, in a climate of overt violence and intimidation by the Fascists, the PPI was dissolved.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] De Gasperi was arrested in March 1927 and sentenced to four years in prison.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] A year and a half in prison nearly broke De Gasperi's health.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] After his release in July 1928, he was unemployed and in serious financial hardship, until in 1929 his ecclesiastical contacts secured him a job as a cataloger in the Vatican Library, where he spent the next fourteen years until the collapse of Fascism in July 1943.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] During the 1930s, De Gasperi wrote a regular international column for the review *L'Illustrazione Vaticana* in which he depicted the chief political battle as one between communism and Christianity.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In 1934, he rejoiced in the defeat of the Austrian Social Democrats, whom he condemned for "de-Christianizing" the country, and in 1937 he declared that the German Church was correct in preferring Nazism to Bolshevism.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] During World War II, he organized the establishment of the first (and at the time, illegal) Christian Democracy (DC) party, drawing upon the ideology of the PPI.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In January 1943, he published "Ideas for Reconstruction" (Italian: *Idee per la Ricostruzione*), which amounted to a program for the party.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] He became the first general secretary of the new party in 1944.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] De Gasperi was the undisputed head of the Christian Democrats, the party that dominated Parliament for decades.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] Although his control of the DC appeared almost complete, he had to carefully balance different factions and interests, especially with regard to relations with the Vatican, social reform, and foreign policy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] When Southern Italy was liberated by the Allies, he became one of the main representatives of DC in the National Liberation Committee.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] During the government led by Ivanoe Bonomi, De Gasperi was appointed minister without portfolio and, in Ferruccio Parri's cabinet, he became minister of foreign affairs.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] From 1945 to 1953, he was the prime minister of eight successive DC-led governments.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] His eight-year rule remains a landmark of political longevity for one leader in modern Italian politics.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] During his successive governments, Italy became a republic (1946), signed a peace treaty with the Allies (1947), joined NATO in 1949 and became an ally of the United States, which helped to revive the Italian economy through the Marshall Plan.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] During that time, Italy became a member of the European Coal and Steel Community (ECSC), which later evolved into the European Union (EU).
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] Crucial in this regard was the contribution of Defense Minister Randolfo Pacciardi, a 30th degree Mason of the Scottish Rite, who had been personally chosen by De Gasperi.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] Communist leader Palmiro Togliatti acted as deputy prime minister.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] He tried to soften the terms of the pending Allied peace treaty with Italy and secured financial and economic aid through the European Recovery Program (Marshall Plan) – which was opposed by the Communists.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In June 1946, a constitutional referendum to decide whether Italy would remain a monarchy or become a republic resulted in 54% of the vote favouring a republic.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] De Gasperi served as provisional head of state from 12 June 1946 until the Constituent Assembly elected Liberal politician Enrico De Nicola provisional head of state on 28 June 1946.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] As chief of the Italian delegation at the World War II peace conference in Paris, De Gasperi harshly criticized the sanctions imposed on Italy, but obtained concessions from the Allies that guaranteed Italian sovereignty.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] Under the Treaty of Peace with Italy, 1947, the eastern border area was lost to Yugoslavia and the free territory of Trieste was divided between the two states.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] One of his most striking achievements in foreign policy was the Gruber-De Gasperi Agreement with Austria in September 1946, which established his home region, South Tyrol, as an autonomous region.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] De Gasperi had considerable support in the US, where he was considered able to oppose the rising tide of communism – in particular the PCI, which was the biggest communist party in a Western European democracy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The chief goals of the trip were to soften the terms of the pending peace treaty with Italy and to obtain immediate economic assistance.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] His ten-day tour, engineered by media mogul Henry Luce – the owner of *Time* magazine – and his wife, Clare Boothe Luce – the future ambassador to Rome – was viewed as a media "triumph", prompting positive comments by a wide section of the American press.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] During his meetings in the United States, De Gasperi managed to secure a financially modest but politically significant US$100 million Eximbank loan to Italy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] According to De Gasperi, public opinion would view the loan as a vote of confidence in the Italian Government and strengthen his position versus the PCI in the context of the emerging Cold War.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The positive results strengthened De Gasperi's reputation in Italy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] He also came back with useful information on the incipient change in American foreign policy that would lead to the Cold War and in Italy the break with the PCI and left-wing PSI and their removal from the government in the May 1947 crisis.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The general elections in April 1948 were heavily influenced by the Cold War era confrontation between the Soviet Union and the United States.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] After the Soviet-orchestrated February 1948 Communist coup in Czechoslovakia, the US became alarmed about Soviet intentions and feared that, if the left-wing coalition were to win the elections, the Soviet-funded PCI would draw Italy into the Soviet Union's sphere of influence.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In the United States, a campaign was launched to prevent a victory of the Communist-dominated Popular Democratic Front (FDP).
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] Italian Americans were encouraged to write letters to their relatives in Italy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The popular Italian-American singer Frank Sinatra made a Voice of America radio broadcast.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The Central Intelligence Agency (CIA) funnelled "black bag" contributions to anti-communist candidates with the approval of the National Security Council and President Harry S.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] Kennedy and Clare Booth Luce helped to raise US$2 million for the Christian Democracy party.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] *Time* magazine backed the campaign and featured De Gasperi on its 19 April 1948 issue's cover and in its lead story.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] He would appear on a *Time* cover again on 25 May 1953, during the campaign for that year's election, with an extensive biography.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The election campaign remains unmatched in verbal aggression and fanaticism in Italy's history on both sides.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The election was between two competing visions of the future of Italian society.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] On the one hand, a Roman Catholic, conservative and capitalist Italy, represented by the governing Christian Democrats of De Gasperi; on the other, a secular, revolutionary and socialist society, represented by the Popular Democratic Front.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The Christian Democrat campaign claimed that in Communist countries "children send parents to jail", "children are owned by the state", "people eat their own children", and assured voters that disaster would strike Italy if the Left were to take power.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The PCI were *de facto* leading the Popular Democratic Front, and had effectively marginalized the PSI, which eventually suffered because of this in these elections, in terms of parliamentary seats and political power.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The Socialists also had been hurt by the secession of a social-democratic faction led by Giuseppe Saragat, which contested the election with the concurrent list of Socialist Unity.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The PCI had difficulties in restraining its more militant members, who, in the period immediately after the war, had engaged in violent acts of reprisals.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The Christian Democrats won a resounding victory with 48.5% of the vote (their best result ever) and strong majorities in both the Chamber of Deputies and Senate.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The Communists received only half of the votes they had in 1946.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] With absolute majorities in both chambers, De Gasperi could have formed an exclusively Christian Democratic government.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] Instead, he formed a "centrist" coalition with the Liberals, Republicans and Social Democrats.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] De Gasperi formed three ministries, the second in 1950 after the defection of the Liberals, who hoped for more rightist policies, and the third in 1951 after the defection of the Social Democrats, who hoped for more left-wing policies.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] He ruled for five more years, helming four additional coalitions.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] "De Gasperi's policy is patience", according to the foreign news correspondent for *The New York Times*, Anne O'Hare McCormick.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In domestic policy, various ministers of De Gasperi's cabinets carried out a number of social security reforms in the areas of rents and social housing, unemployment insurance, and pensions.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In 1952, the party overwhelmingly endorsed his authority over the government and over the party.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] However, it was also the start of his decline.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] He came under increasing criticism from the emerging left wing in the party.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] Their main accusations were that he was too cautious in social and economic reform, that he stifled debate and that he subordinated the party to the interests of government.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The 1953 general election was characterised by changes in the electoral law.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] Even if the general structure remained uncorrupted, the government introduced a superbonus of two-thirds of seats in the House for the coalition which would obtain at-large the absolute majority of votes.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The change was strongly opposed by the opposition parties as well as DC's smaller coalition partners, who had no realistic chance of success under this system.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The new law was called the *Scam Law* by its detractors, including some dissidents of minor government parties who founded special opposition groups to deny the artificial landslide to Christian Democracy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The Holy See actively supported Christian Democracy, declaring that it would be a mortal sin for a Catholic to vote for the PCI and excommunicating all its supporters.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In practice, however, many Communists remained religious: Emilia was known to be an area where people were both religious and communists.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] Giovannino Guareschi wrote his novels about Don Camillo describing a village, Brescello, whose inhabitants are at the same time loyal to priest Camillo and Communist mayor Peppone, who are fierce rivals.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The campaign of the opposition to the "Scam Law" achieved its goal.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The government coalition (DC, PSDI, PLI, PRI, South Tyrolean People's Party and Sardinian Action Party) won 49.9% of the national vote, just a few thousand votes from the threshold for a supermajority, resulting in an ordinary proportional distribution of the seats.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] Minor dissident parties determined the final result, especially the short-lived National Democratic Alliance.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The leading party Christian Democracy did not repeat the extraordinary result of five years earlier, which had been obtained under special conditions linked to the Cold War, and lost a lot of votes to the right, including resurgent fascist politicians, particularly in Southern Italy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] Technically, the government won the election, winning a clear working majority of seats in both houses.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] However, frustration with the failure to win a supermajority caused significant tensions in the leading coalition.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] De Gasperi was forced to resign by the Parliament on 2 August: he consequently retired and died twelve months later.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The legislature continued with weak governments, with minor parties refusing institutional responsibilities.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] Giuseppe Pella rose to power, but fell after only five months, following heated disputes about the status of the Free Territory of Trieste which Pella was claiming.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The parliamentary term was seen out by the minority government chaired by Adone Zoli, finishing a legislature which hugely weakened the office of the Prime Minister, held by six different leaders.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In 1954, De Gasperi also had to give up the leadership of the party, when Amintore Fanfani was appointed new Secretary of the Christian Democracy in June.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] On 19 August 1954, De Gasperi died in Sella di Valsugana, in his beloved Trentino.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] It is said that he had to be given a State funeral as he had died with almost no means of his own.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] He is buried in the Basilica di San Lorenzo fuori le Mura, a basilica in Rome.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The process for his beatification was opened in 1993.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] "De Gasperi was against exacerbating conflict", according to his former secretary and former Prime Minister Giulio Andreotti.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] He is considered one of the founding fathers of the European Union.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] From the very beginning of European integration, De Gasperi, Robert Schuman and Konrad Adenauer met regularly.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] He helped to organize the Council of Europe and supported the Schuman Declaration, which in 1951 led to the foundation of the European Coal and Steel Community – a forerunner in the process of European integration.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In 1954 he was elected president of the forerunner of the European Parliament, the Community's Common Assembly.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] Although eventually transformed into the current project of the European Union, De Gasperi helped to develop the idea of a common European defence policy.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In 1952, he received the Karlspreis (International Charlemagne Prize of the City of Aachen), an award by the German city of Aachen to people who contributed to the European idea and European peace.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] The 1954–1955 academic year at the College of Europe was named in his honour.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In 2024, a 515-page revisionist account of De Gasperi by Mark Gilbert, *"Italy Reborn; from Fascism to Democracy"*, was published by Allen Lane.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] On 14 June 1922, De Gasperi married Francesca Romani (30 August 1894 – 20 August 1998) and had four daughters, Maria Romana, Lucia, Cecilia and Paola.
[src:alcide-de-gasperi/alcide-de-gasperi] In Florestano Vancini's film *The Assassination of Matteotti* (1973), De Gasperi is played by Ezio Marano.
